{"title_page": "Federal Prison Camp, Alderson", "text_new": "{{Infobox Prison\n| prison_name    = Federal Prison Camp, Alderson\n| image          = Alderson Federal Prison Camp entrance.jpg\n| image_size     = 250\n| location       = Monroe and Summers Counties, West Virginia\n| coordinates    = \n| status         = Operational\n| classification = Minimum-security\n| population     = 966<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/ald/ |title=FPC Alderson |work=Federal Bureau of Prisons }}</ref>\n| opened         = 1928\n| closed         = \n| managed_by     = [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]\n| warden         = D. Wilson\n}}\n[[File:Alderson Federal Prison.jpg|thumb|Aerial view]]\n[[File:FPCAldersonDorm.jpg|thumb|Administration building]]\nThe '''Federal Prison Camp, Alderson''' ('''FPC Alderson''') is a minimum-security United States [[federal prison]] [[Incarceration of women in the United States|for female inmates]] in [[West Virginia]]. It is operated by the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]], a division of the [[United States Department of Justice]].\n\nFPC Alderson is in two West Virginia counties, near the town of [[Alderson, West Virginia|Alderson]]. A portion of the prison is in [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] [[Monroe County, West Virginia|Monroe County]], while the other portion of the prison, including the dormitories, is in unincorporated [[Summers County, West Virginia|Summers County]].<ref name=\"MarthaThank\">{{cite web| url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-125332430.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102203613/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-125332430.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=2 November 2012 |title=Martha's Prison Thanksgiving |publisher=Highbeam (The Cincinnati Post)| date=24 November 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011 |quote=Mullins said the prison dormitories are in Summers County }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bop.gov/DataSource/execute/dsFacilityAddressLoc?start=y&facilityCode=ald |title=FPC Alderson Contact Information |publisher=Federal Bureau of Prisons |accessdate=2 October 2011 }}</ref> Four other area towns, [[Hinton, West Virginia|Hinton]], [[Lewisburg, West Virginia|Lewisburg]], [[Ronceverte, West Virginia|Ronceverte]], and [[White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia|White Sulphur Springs]], are within commuting distance of FPC Alderson.<ref name=\"AldersonInfo\">{{cite web|url= http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/ald/index.jsp |title=FPC Alderson |publisher=Federal Bureau of Prison |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:FPCAldersonTopographical.PNG|thumb|right|Topographic map, [[U.S. Geological Survey]], July 1, 1983]]\nIn the 1920s, there was a shortage of federal prison space for female inmates.<ref name=\"johnson\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7mkMQh9ZMhsC&pg=PA313&dq=Federal+prisons+for+women+also+lagged+behind+their+male+counterparts |page=313 |title=Inner lives: voices of African American women in prison |first=Paula C. |last=Johnson |year=2004 |publisher=New York University Press |isbn= 978-0-8147-4255-6 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref> Women offenders either were given alternative punishments or were housed alone within all-male institutions. Prison staff and fellow inmates sexually exploited girls and women who were incarcerated in these facilities.<ref name=\"johnson\"/>\n\n[[Mabel Walker Willebrandt]], the [[United States Assistant Attorney General|Assistant U.S. Attorney General]], first encouraged establishment of a facility for women.<ref name=\"sicherman\">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CfGHM9KU7aEC&pg=PA736&dq=energy+resourcefulness+led+establishment+West+Virginia+Alderson+first+federal+prison+women+first+warden+MARY+HARRIS |accessdate=17 July 2011 |page=736 |title=Notable American women: the modern period : a biographical dictionary |volume=4 |first=Barbara |last=Sicherman |first2=Carol Hurd |last2=Green|year=1980 |isbn=9780674627338 }}</ref> FPC Alderson, which opened on April 30, 1927, as the Federal Industrial Institute for Women,<ref name=\"Friedman1994\">{{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Lawrence|title=Crime And Punishment In American History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sGL04_iELikC&pg=PA428|accessdate=2018-04-28|date=1994-09-09|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=9780465024469|page=428| df=mdy-all}}</ref> was the first federal women's prison in the United States.<ref>{{cite news| last=Keller |first=Julia |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/703554631.html?dids=703554631:703554631&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |title=It's a gosh-darned good thing: Stewart heads to West Virginia |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=1 October 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref> It was opened during a reform movement in the 1920s to help reform female offenders.<ref name=\"marks\">{{cite news |last=Marks |first=Alexandra |title=The prison that Martha Stewart will call home |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2004/1008/p01s01-usju.html |date=8 October 2004 |work=The Christian Science Monitor |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe first warden, Mary B. Harris, was chosen by Mabel Willebrandt.<ref name=\"sicherman\"/> \nDespite later bureau mythology that Alderson opened its doors with [[Moonshine|moonshining]] women from the hills of West Virginia, 174 women had been sent to the facility in the first year of operation before its formal November 14, 1928, opening.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8pbaAAAAMAAJ&q=Despite+the+later+bureau+mythology+that+Alderson+opened+its+doors+with+moonshining+women+from+the+hills+of+West+Virginia |page=51 |title=Escaping prison myths: selected topics in the history of federal corrections |first=John Walter |last=Roberts |year=1994 |publisher=American University Press |isbn= 978-1-879383-27-2 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> The West Virginia location was chosen as it was remote enough from major population centers that potential escapes would be less likely while it had sufficient proximity to the American capital.<ref name=Vargasstoried>{{cite news|author=Vargas, Theresa|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/09/beyond-orange-is-the-new-black-the-storied-past-of-alderson-federal-womens-prison/|title=Beyond 'Orange Is the New Black': The storied past of Alderson federal women's prison|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2017-06-09|accessdate=2017-08-04}}</ref>\n\nServing as a model for prison reform at the time, it was styled after a [[boarding school]] offering education with no armed guards.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=5kjkZjvnI-sC&pg=PA155&dq=Alderson+a+model+for+prison+reform+it+was+styled+after+a+boarding+school |page=155 |title=Timelines of American women's history |first=Sue |last=Heinemann |publisher=Penguin Group|year=1995 |isbn= 978-0-399-51986-4 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> The facility followed a reformatory model with no fenced grounds.<ref name=\"johnson\"/> The prison consisted of primarily work-oriented facilities designed for minor federal offenders. It originally consisted of fourteen [[cottage]]s built in a [[horseshoe]] pattern on two-tiered slopes.<ref name=\"aca\">{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SmBHAAAAMAAJ&q=Located+in+rural+West+Virginia,+Alderson+consisted+of+fourteen+cottages+(offenders+were+segregated+by+race)+built |title=Female offenders: meeting needs of a neglected population |author=American Correctional Association |year=1993 |isbn= 978-0-929310-86-2 |page=18 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref> The offenders segregated by race in the cottages and each building contained a kitchen and rooms for about thirty women.<ref name=\"aca\"/> The vast majority of the women were imprisoned for drug and alcohol charges imposed during the Prohibition era.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/the-first-federal-prison-for-women-opens |title=This-day-in-history - The first federal prison for women opens |publisher=history.com |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Facility==\n[[File:AldersonAerial.PNG|thumb|Aerial view, USGS, October 27, 1990]]\nFPC Alderson is a {{convert|159|acre|ha|adj=on}} facility and is the largest employer in the [[Alderson, West Virginia]] area.<ref name=\"WelcomeWashTimes\">\"{{cite web|url=http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-849399/Welcome-to-Alderson-Stewart-began.html |first=Marguerite |last=Higgins |title=Welcome to Alderson; Stewart began her five months before dawn at W.Va. prison |publisher=Goliath (The Washington Times) |date=9 October 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> The prison is about a five-hour driving distance from [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=Vargasstoried />\n\nWhile there is no barbed wire on the fence surrounding the camp, the prisoners have schedules and each one must work. Inmates get holidays off except those who work in the powerhouse and kitchen.<ref name=\"helderman \" /> From its beginning, Alderson's staff members have maintained a focus on vocational training and personal growth experiences, with craft-shop activities an integral part of vocational training.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/ald/ALD_aohandbook.pdf |title=FPC Alderson Inmate Handbook |page=2 |date=10 November 2010 |publisher=Federal Prison Camp Alderson |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> Free time is spent walking around the sidewalk that is set between the two dorms as this is within bounds for the inmates. Since 2004 inmates are no longer free to roam the entire campus and are restricted in areas of the prison. They also play recreational activities such as [[volleyball]].\n\nMost of the inmates at FPC Alderson have been convicted of non-violent or [[white-collar crime]]. Many are in the drug program and have come from other prisons to attend the program at Alderson. They sleep in [[bunk bed]]s in two large [[dormitories]]. The dormitories hold 500 plus inmates a piece. Each inmate sleeps in a {{convert|5|x|9|ft|m|adj=on}} [[Concrete masonry unit|cinderblock]] cube inside of this open dormitory.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nThe prison was nicknamed \"Camp [[Cupcake]]\" by members of the news media when Martha Stewart was sentenced to a five-month term there.<ref name=\"thompson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/6196954 |last=Thompson |first=Anne |title=Ultimate planner set to lose control of her life: Martha Stewart won't mistake 'Camp Cupcake' for the Hamptons |publisher=NBC News |date=7 October 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> Local residents have also referred to it as \"the college campus.\"<ref name=\"thompson\" /> It was called \"[[Yale University|Yale]]\" by one-time attendee [[Martha Stewart]].<ref name=\"Yale\">{{cite news|url= http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/09/20/entertainment/main860422.shtml |last=de Vries |first=Lloyd |title=How Martha Coped At 'Yale' |publisher=CBS News |date=20 September 2005 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> By 2004, according to Alexandra Marks of ''[[The Independent]]'', the operating model for Alderson followed \"a punitive rather than a rehabilitative model\".<ref name=\"marks\" />\n\nJohn Benish, the former co-manager of the Alderson Hospitality House, a hospitality establishment where families of Alderson inmates stay, said that FPC Alderson is \"built like a college campus. There is lot of property, a lot of greenery and there is no [[barbed wire]] around.\" The Alderson facility includes two dormitories with 500 inmates each. Inmates live in two person cubicles instead of traditional barred prison cells.<ref>{{cite news|last=Meier |first=Barry |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C05E5D81538F933A0575AC0A9629C8B63 |title=Martha Stewart Assigned to Prison in West Virginia |newspaper=The New York Times |date=30 September 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2004, most prisoners at Alderson were convicted of [[recreational drug]]-related offenses. Esther Heffernan, a sociology professor at [[Edgewood College]], said that throughout history the inmates included \"relatives of famous mobsters and grandmotherly women who embezzled money from banks. You've had a real mixture.\" Hefferman added that in Alderson, which was a \"not undesirable\" place to be confined, the isolation from urban life could be stressful for inmates. She said that the inmates, \"Coming from the streets of [[New York City|New York]] and [[Washington, D.C.|D.C.]],\" were awakened at night by crickets and frogs.<ref>{{cite news|last=Crawford |first=Krysten |url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/09/29/news/newsmakers/martha/index.htm |title=Martha going to 'Camp Cupcake' |publisher=CNN/Money |date=29 September 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> Prisoners are not permitted to patronize Alderson, West Virginia area businesses.<ref>{{cite news|last=Keller |first=Julia |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/703554631.html?dids=703554631:703554631&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |title=It's a gosh-darned good thing: Stewart heads to West Virginia |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=1 October 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011 |quote=They're forbidden to frequent Alderson businesses, so Simms has never trimmed a...}}</ref>\n\nThe facility allows weekend visits, but special hours are available for holidays.<ref name=\"helderman \">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A8664-2004Nov23.html |title=Domestic Diva to Spend Thanksgiving Inside \u2013 Turkey, Few Trimmings For Jailed Media Mogul |first=Rosalind S. |last=Helderman |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=24 November 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> In prior years the families of inmates were allowed past visiting rooms only on [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving Day]] when they could also share in a holiday feast for $1.75.<ref name=\"helderman \" />\n\nFPC Alderson was one of six federal and state prisons participating in the Paws4prisons service dog training program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kyria|title=Some of the DOGs' activities at Federal Prison Camp Alderson (WV) |url= https://paws4people.org/tag/federal-prison-camp/ |website=paws4people foundation|accessdate=23 October 2017 |date=August 22, 2011}}</ref> This program allowed inmates the opportunity to interact and work with dogs.<ref>{{cite web |last=Asbury |first=Kyla |title=Inmate, afraid of dogs, loses lawsuit over broken leg |url= https://wvrecord.com/stories/510606118-inmate-afraid-of-dogs-loses-lawsuit-over-broken-leg |publisher=West Virginia Record |date=22 October 2013 |accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref> This included an academic curriculum where inmates first learn how to train \"shelter-rescue dogs\" and then progress to developing highly trained assistance dogs.<ref>{{cite web |title=The paws4prisons Program |url= https://paws4people.org/our-programs/paws4prisons/ |website=paws4people.org |accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable inmates (current and former)==\n* Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.\n\n===Violent criminals===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Lolita Lebr\u00f3n]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=22167-069&x=66&y=13 22167-069]\n| Sentence [[commutation of sentence|commuted]] by President [[Jimmy Carter]] in 1979; served 25 years.\n| Member of a group of [[Puerto Rican independence movement|Puerto Rican nationalists]] who opened fire inside the [[US House of Representatives]] in 1954, wounding five Congressmen; served additional prison time in 2001 for trespassing on military property for protesting the [[US Navy]] presence on the Puerto Rican island of [[Vieques]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/03/us/03lebron.html | work=The New York Times | first=Douglas | last=Martin | title=Lolita Lebr\u00f3n, Puerto Rican Nationalist, Dies at 90 | date=3 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_62IjQ-XQScC&pg=PA381&dq=Lolita+Lebr\u00f3n+Alderson+WV |title=Latinas in the United States: a historical encyclopedia |volume=1 |first=Vicki |last=Ru\u00edz |first2=Virginia S\u00e1nchez |last2=Korrol |page=381 |publisher=Indiana University Press |year=2006 |isbn= 978-0-253-34681-0 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[George Weyerhaeuser kidnapping|Margaret Waley]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| Released from custody in 1948 after serving 14 years.\n| Convicted in 1935 of [[kidnapping]] and [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] for her role as an accomplice in the [[George Weyerhaeuser kidnapping|kidnapping of George Weyerhaeuser]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McClary |first=Daryl C. |url=http://www.historylink.org/_content/study_aids/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=7711 |title=the Free Online Encyclopedia of Washington State History |publisher=HistoryLink.org |date=2006-03-27 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Kathryn Kelly]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| Released from custody in 1958 after serving 25 years.\n| Wife of notorious bank robber and murderer George Kelly Barnes, better known as \"[[Machine Gun Kelly]];\" convicted in 1933 of being her husband's accomplice in the [[kidnapping]] of businessman and oil tycoon [[Charles F. Urschel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dillingerswomen.com/articles/kathryn.html |title=Don't Call Us Molls: Kathryn Kelly |publisher=Dillingerswomen.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Lynette Fromme]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=06075-180&x=69&y=26 06075-180]\n| Spent the majority of her sentence at FPC Alderson; released in 2009 after serving 34 years.\n| Follower of [[cult leader]] and [[serial killer]] [[Charles Manson]]; attempted to [[assassinate]] U.S. President [[Gerald Ford]] on September 5, 1975; known by the nickname \"Squeaky.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Busted: Mugshots and Arrest Records of the Famous and Infamous |first=Thomas J. |last=Craughwell |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ll-1WrZvUwsC&pg=PA156&dq=Lynette+Fromme+Alderson+WV |page=156 |publisher=Black Dog & Leventhal|year=2011 |isbn= 978-1-57912-865-4 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-201_162-5241905.html |title=Manson Disciple \"Squeaky\" Fromme Set Free |publisher=CBS News |date=2009-08-14 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Sara Jane Moore]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=04851-180&x=84&y=22 04851-180]\n| imprisoned 1975\u201378, in 1979 she escaped and was recaptured hours later;<ref>{{cite news|url= https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/649221072.html?dids=649221072:649221072&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+06%2C+1979&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Sara+Jane+Moore+Flees%2C+Is+Caught |title=Sara Jane Moore Flees, Is Caught |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=6 February 1979 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> released in 2007, after serving 32 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/12/31/moore.release/index.html|title=Would-be Ford assassin freed from prison on parole - CNN.com|website=www.cnn.com|language=en|access-date=2017-06-09}}</ref>\n| Attempted to assassinate U.S. President [[Gerald Ford]] on September 22, 1975.\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Espionage, Smith Act and \"Supporting the Enemy in Wartime\" prisoners===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Velvalee Dickinson]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}} \n|imprisoned 1944\u20131951<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/about-us/history/famous-cases/velvalee-dickinson-doll-woman |title=Velvalee Dickinson, the \"Doll Woman\" |publisher=FBI |accessdate=17 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502073409/http://www.fbi.gov/about-us/history/famous-cases/velvalee-dickinson-doll-woman |archivedate=2 May 2013 }}</ref>\n| American convicted of espionage against the United States on behalf of Japan.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Iva Toguri D'Aquino]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| Was Held in FPC, Alderson<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F5wukQLkavoC&pg=PA433&dq=Iva+Toguri+D'Aquino+Alderson+WV |title=American women during World War II: an encyclopedia |first= Doris |last=Weatherford |page=433 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2009 |isbn= 978-0-415-99475-0 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n| American citizen who participated in English-language [[propaganda]] broadcast transmitted by Radio Tokyo to Allied soldiers in the South Pacific during [[World War II]]; known as \"Tokyo Rose.\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Mildred Gillars]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n|imprisoned 1950\u201356<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mcbRtSJ2EDkC&pg=PA223&dq=Mildred+Gillars+Alderson+WV |title=Axis Sally: The American Voice of Nazi Germany |first=Richard |last=Lucas |publisher=Casemate Publishers |year=2010 |isbn= 978-1-935149-43-9 |pages=223, 292 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/01/obituaries/mildred-gillars-87-axis-sally-during-war.html|title=Obituaries: Mildred Gillars, 87, Axis Sally During War |newspaper=The New York Times |date=1 July 1988 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n| American who supplied propaganda broadcasts for [[Nazi Germany]]; known as \"Axis Sally.\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Elizabeth Gurley Flynn]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| imprisoned 1955\u201357<ref>{{cite book|title=The Alderson story: my life as a political prisoner |first=Elizabeth Gurley |last=Flynn |publisher=International Publishers |year=1963}}</ref>\n| American leftist leader and co-founder of [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU), a [[Smith Act]] prisoner\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Claudia Jones]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| imprisoned 1955\u201357<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackhistorymonthuk.co.uk/features/claudia_jones.html|title=Claudia Jones|publisher=Black History Month|accessdate=29 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019212347/http://www.blackhistorymonthuk.co.uk/features/claudia_jones.html|archive-date=19 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| Trinidadian-born child-immigrant journalist and National Executive member of the [[Communist Party of the United States]], a Smith Act prisoner. After release, deported to the [[United Kingdom]], founded the [[Notting Hill Carnival]]\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Corrupt public officials===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Monica Conyers]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=43693-039&x=94&y=13 43693-039]\n| Released from custody on May 16, 2013 after serving 3 years.\n| [[Detroit City Council]] member from 2005 to 2009 and wife of former-Congressman [[John Conyers]]; pleaded guilty to [[bribery]] in 2009 for accepting $60,000 from a waste management company in return for her helping the company win a $1.2&nbsp;billion contract with the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/story?id=7938249&page=1#.UB4nWVJdDyI |title=Monica Conyers, Wife of Judiciary Chairman Rep. John Conyers Pleads Guilty to Bribery - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2009-06-26 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/10/monica-conyers-wife-to-jo_n_494305.html|title=Monica Conyers, Wife To John Conyers, Sentenced To 3 Years In Prison For Detroit Bribes|date=May 10, 2010|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Meg Scott Phipps]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=23786-056&x=82&y=6 23786-056]\n| Released from custody in 2007 after serving 3 years.\n| [[North Carolina Department of Agriculture & Consumer Services|North Carolina Agriculture Commissioner]] from 2001 to 2003; pleaded guilty in 2003 to [[extortion]], [[mail fraud]], and [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] for accepting thousands of dollars in illegal cash payments, falsifying campaign finance reports, and extorting money from carnival operators with the promise of state contracts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/news/local/story/109254/ |title=Phipps To Spend Four Years In Prison For State Ag Department Scandal |publisher=WRAL.com |date=2004-03-02 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digtriad.com/news/article/83437/0/Meg-Scott-Phipps-Released-From-Prison |title=Meg Scott Phipps Released From Prison |publisher=digtriad.com |date=2007-04-23 |accessdate=2015-10-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130121105945/http://www.digtriad.com/news/article/83437/0/Meg-Scott-Phipps-Released-From-Prison |archivedate=2013-01-21 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Financial criminals===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Stacey Pomrenke]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 19241-084<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/ | title=Inmate Locator | author= | publisher=bop.gov | date= | accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n|Released in 2018 after serving a 23-month sentence.\n|Former Bristol Virginia Utilities (BVU) Chief Financial Officer (CFO) convicted on one count of conspiracy to commit tax fraud, three counts of making false statements to the IRS, one count of program fraud, two counts of extortion, one count of conspiracy to commit wire fraud and six counts of wire fraud.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Martha Stewart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=55170-054&x=69&y=25 55170-054]\n| Released from custody in 2005 after serving 5 months. \n| American business magnate, television host, author, and magazine publisher; convicted in 2004 of [[obstruction of justice]] and lying to federal prosecutors investigating [[insider trading]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/03/05/news/companies/martha_verdict/ | work=CNN | title=Stewart convicted on all charges | date=5 March 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A54591-2004Jul16.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Martha Stewart Sentenced to 5 Months in Prison | date=16 July 2004}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Esther Reed]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=40024-424&x=80&y=21 40024-424]\n| Released from custody in 2011 after serving 3 years.\n| Former [[US Secret Service]] Most-Wanted Fugitive; pleaded guilty to [[fraud]] and [[identity theft]] for falsely assuming several identities, including that of missing person Brooke Henson, in order to steal money and gain entrance to [[Ivy League]] universities; Reed was featured on the television program ''[[America's Most Wanted]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.secretservice.gov/FY2008_AnnualReport_WM.pdf|title=United States Secret Service Fiscal Year 2008 Annual Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825185354/http://www.secretservice.gov/FY2008_AnnualReport_WM.pdf|archive-date=August 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1473463/|title=America's Most Wanted: America Fights Back : Esther Reed Capture|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Diane Hathaway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=Diane&Middle=&LastName=Hathaway&Race=W&Sex=F&Age=&x=90&y=11 48069-039]\n| Released from custody in 2014 after serving 366 days.\n| [[Michigan Supreme Court|Former Michigan Supreme Court Justice]] convicted of mortgage fraud.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ross Jones |url=http://www.wxyz.com/dpp/news/local_news/investigations/with-hathaway-now-a-felon-gov-snyder-mulls-her-replacement |title=With Hathaway now a felon, Gov. Snyder mulls her replacement |publisher=WXYZ.com |date=2013-01-30 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Others===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Billie Holiday]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| imprisoned 1947-48<ref>{{cite book |title=Billie Holiday |first=Magdalena |last=Alagna |pages=60\u201370 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lh3rwxxv2z0C&pg=PT72&dq=Billie+Holiday+Alderson+WV |publisher=Rosen Publishing |year=2003 |isbn= 978-0-8239-3640-3 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n| American jazz singer and songwriter arrested for possession of narcotics on May 19, 1947 and sentenced to serve a year and a day, but released for good behavior on March 16, 1948.\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Incarceration in the United States]]\n*[[List of U.S. federal prisons]]\n{{Portal|United States|Politics}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons-inline|Federal Prison Camp, Alderson}}\n*[http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/ald/index.jsp FPC Alderson] - [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/ald/ALD_aohandbook.pdf |title=FPC Alderson Inmate Handbook |date=10 November 2010 |publisher=Federal Prison Camp Alderson |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DludRuOG?url=http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/ald/ALD_aohandbook.pdf |archivedate=2013-01-18 }} ()\n*{{cite web|url=http://seniorwomen.com/articles/articlesHanrahanAlderson.html |title=Alderson: Reclaiming the Vision |first=Clare |last=Hanrahan | publisher=SeniorWomen.com|year=2003}}\n*{{HABS |survey=WV-113 |id=wv0211 |title=Federal Reformatory for Women, State Route 3, South of Greenbriar River, Alderson vicinity, Summers, WV}}\n*{{HABS |survey=WV-113-A |id=wv0247 |title=Federal Reformatory for Women, Administration Building |link=no}}\n*{{HABS |survey=WV-113-B |id=wv0248 |title=Federal Reformatory for Women, School & Chapel |link=no}}\n*{{HABS |survey=WV-113-C |id=wv0249 |title=Federal Reformatory for Women, Cottages |link=no}}\n*{{HABS |survey=WV-113-D |id=wv0250 |title=Federal Reformatory for Women, Warden's House |link=no}}\n\n{{coord|37|43|25|N|80|40|04|W|scale:10000|display=title}}\n{{Federal Bureau of Prisons}}\n{{Women's prisons in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Women's prisons in the United States|Alderson, Federal]]\n[[Category:Federal Prison Camps|Alderson]]\n[[Category:Prisons in West Virginia|Alderson, Federal]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Monroe County, West Virginia|Alderson, Federal]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Summers County, West Virginia|Alderson, Federal]]\n[[Category:Historic American Buildings Survey in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in West Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Prison\n| prison_name    = Federal Prison Camp, Alderson\n| image          = Alderson Federal Prison Camp entrance.jpg\n| image_size     = 250\n| location       = Monroe and Summers Counties, West Virginia\n| coordinates    = \n| status         = Operational\n| classification = Minimum-security\n| population     = 966<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/ald/ |title=FPC Alderson |work=Federal Bureau of Prisons }}</ref>\n| opened         = 1928\n| closed         = \n| managed_by     = [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]\n| warden         = D. Wilson\n}}\n[[File:Alderson Federal Prison.jpg|thumb|Aerial view]]\n[[File:FPCAldersonDorm.jpg|thumb|Administration building]]\nThe '''Federal Prison Camp, Alderson''' ('''FPC Alderson''') is a minimum-security United States [[federal prison]] [[Incarceration of women in the United States|for female inmates]] in [[West Virginia]]. It is operated by the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]], a division of the [[United States Department of Justice]].\n\nFPC Alderson is located in two West Virginia counties, near the town of [[Alderson, West Virginia|Alderson]]. A portion of the prison is located in [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] [[Monroe County, West Virginia|Monroe County]], while the other portion of the prison, including the dormitories, lies in unincorporated [[Summers County, West Virginia|Summers County]].<ref name=\"MarthaThank\">{{cite web| url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-125332430.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102203613/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-125332430.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=2 November 2012 |title=Martha's Prison Thanksgiving |publisher=Highbeam (The Cincinnati Post)| date=24 November 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011 |quote=Mullins said the prison dormitories are in Summers County }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bop.gov/DataSource/execute/dsFacilityAddressLoc?start=y&facilityCode=ald |title=FPC Alderson Contact Information |publisher=Federal Bureau of Prisons |accessdate=2 October 2011 }}</ref> Four other area towns, [[Hinton, West Virginia|Hinton]], [[Lewisburg, West Virginia|Lewisburg]], [[Ronceverte, West Virginia|Ronceverte]], and [[White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia|White Sulphur Springs]], are within commuting distance of FPC Alderson.<ref name=\"AldersonInfo\">{{cite web|url= http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/ald/index.jsp |title=FPC Alderson |publisher=Federal Bureau of Prison |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:FPCAldersonTopographical.PNG|thumb|right|Topographic map, [[U.S. Geological Survey]], July 1, 1983]]\nIn the 1920s, there was a shortage of federal prison space for female inmates.<ref name=\"johnson\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7mkMQh9ZMhsC&pg=PA313&dq=Federal+prisons+for+women+also+lagged+behind+their+male+counterparts |page=313 |title=Inner lives: voices of African American women in prison |first=Paula C. |last=Johnson |year=2004 |publisher=New York University Press |isbn= 978-0-8147-4255-6 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref> Women offenders either were given alternative punishments or were housed alone within all-male institutions. Prison staff and fellow inmates sexually exploited girls and women who were incarcerated in these facilities.<ref name=\"johnson\"/>\n\n[[Mabel Walker Willebrandt]], the [[United States Assistant Attorney General|Assistant U.S. Attorney General]], first encouraged establishment of a facility for women.<ref name=\"sicherman\">{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=CfGHM9KU7aEC&pg=PA736&dq=energy+resourcefulness+led+establishment+West+Virginia+Alderson+first+federal+prison+women+first+warden+MARY+HARRIS |accessdate=17 July 2011 |page=736 |title=Notable American women: the modern period : a biographical dictionary |volume=4 |first=Barbara |last=Sicherman |first2=Carol Hurd |last2=Green|year=1980 |isbn=9780674627338 }}</ref> FPC Alderson, which opened on April 30, 1927, as the Federal Industrial Institute for Women,<ref name=\"Friedman1994\">{{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Lawrence|title=Crime And Punishment In American History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sGL04_iELikC&pg=PA428|accessdate=2018-04-28|date=1994-09-09|publisher=Basic Books|isbn=9780465024469|page=428| df=mdy-all}}</ref> was the first federal women's prison in the United States.<ref>{{cite news| last=Keller |first=Julia |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/703554631.html?dids=703554631:703554631&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |title=It's a gosh-darned good thing: Stewart heads to West Virginia |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=1 October 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref> It was opened during a reform movement in the 1920s to help reform female offenders.<ref name=\"marks\">{{cite news |last=Marks |first=Alexandra |title=The prison that Martha Stewart will call home |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2004/1008/p01s01-usju.html |date=8 October 2004 |work=The Christian Science Monitor |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe first warden, Mary B. Harris, was chosen by Mabel Willebrandt.<ref name=\"sicherman\"/> \nDespite later bureau mythology that Alderson opened its doors with [[Moonshine|moonshining]] women from the hills of West Virginia, 174 women had been sent to the facility in the first year of operation before its formal November 14, 1928, opening.<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8pbaAAAAMAAJ&q=Despite+the+later+bureau+mythology+that+Alderson+opened+its+doors+with+moonshining+women+from+the+hills+of+West+Virginia |page=51 |title=Escaping prison myths: selected topics in the history of federal corrections |first=John Walter |last=Roberts |year=1994 |publisher=American University Press |isbn= 978-1-879383-27-2 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> The West Virginia location was chosen as it was remote enough from major population centers that potential escapes would be less likely while it had sufficient proximity to the American capital.<ref name=Vargasstoried>{{cite news|author=Vargas, Theresa|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/retropolis/wp/2017/06/09/beyond-orange-is-the-new-black-the-storied-past-of-alderson-federal-womens-prison/|title=Beyond 'Orange Is the New Black': The storied past of Alderson federal women's prison|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2017-06-09|accessdate=2017-08-04}}</ref>\n\nServing as a model for prison reform at the time, it was styled after a [[boarding school]] offering education with no armed guards.<ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=5kjkZjvnI-sC&pg=PA155&dq=Alderson+a+model+for+prison+reform+it+was+styled+after+a+boarding+school |page=155 |title=Timelines of American women's history |first=Sue |last=Heinemann |publisher=Penguin Group|year=1995 |isbn= 978-0-399-51986-4 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> The facility followed a reformatory model with no fenced grounds.<ref name=\"johnson\"/> The prison consisted of primarily work-oriented facilities designed for minor federal offenders. It originally consisted of fourteen [[cottage]]s built in a [[horseshoe]] pattern on two-tiered slopes.<ref name=\"aca\">{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SmBHAAAAMAAJ&q=Located+in+rural+West+Virginia,+Alderson+consisted+of+fourteen+cottages+(offenders+were+segregated+by+race)+built |title=Female offenders: meeting needs of a neglected population |author=American Correctional Association |year=1993 |isbn= 978-0-929310-86-2 |page=18 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref> The offenders segregated by race in the cottages and each building contained a kitchen and rooms for about thirty women.<ref name=\"aca\"/> The vast majority of the women were imprisoned for drug and alcohol charges imposed during the Prohibition era.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/the-first-federal-prison-for-women-opens |title=This-day-in-history - The first federal prison for women opens |publisher=history.com |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Facility==\n[[File:AldersonAerial.PNG|thumb|Aerial view, USGS, October 27, 1990]]\nFPC Alderson is a {{convert|159|acre|ha|adj=on}} facility and is the largest employer in the [[Alderson, West Virginia]] area.<ref name=\"WelcomeWashTimes\">\"{{cite web|url=http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-849399/Welcome-to-Alderson-Stewart-began.html |first=Marguerite |last=Higgins |title=Welcome to Alderson; Stewart began her five months before dawn at W.Va. prison |publisher=Goliath (The Washington Times) |date=9 October 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> The prison is about a five-hour driving distance from [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=Vargasstoried />\n\nWhile there is no barbed wire on the fence surrounding the camp, the prisoners have schedules and each one must work. Inmates get holidays off except those who work in the powerhouse and kitchen.<ref name=\"helderman \" /> From its beginning, Alderson's staff members have maintained a focus on vocational training and personal growth experiences, with craft-shop activities an integral part of vocational training.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/ald/ALD_aohandbook.pdf |title=FPC Alderson Inmate Handbook |page=2 |date=10 November 2010 |publisher=Federal Prison Camp Alderson |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> Free time is spent walking around the sidewalk that is set between the two dorms as this is within bounds for the inmates. Since 2004 inmates are no longer free to roam the entire campus and are restricted in areas of the prison. They also play recreational activities such as [[volleyball]].\n\nMost of the inmates at FPC Alderson have been convicted of non-violent or [[white-collar crime]]. Many are in the drug program and have come from other prisons to attend the program at Alderson. They sleep in [[bunk bed]]s in two large [[dormitories]]. The dormitories hold 500 plus inmates a piece. Each inmate sleeps in a {{convert|5|x|9|ft|m|adj=on}} [[Concrete masonry unit|cinderblock]] cube inside of this open dormitory.{{Citation needed|date=January 2010}}\n\nThe prison was nicknamed \"Camp [[Cupcake]]\" by members of the news media when Martha Stewart was sentenced to a five-month term there.<ref name=\"thompson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/6196954 |last=Thompson |first=Anne |title=Ultimate planner set to lose control of her life: Martha Stewart won't mistake 'Camp Cupcake' for the Hamptons |publisher=NBC News |date=7 October 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> Local residents have also referred to it as \"the college campus.\"<ref name=\"thompson\" /> It was called \"[[Yale University|Yale]]\" by one-time attendee [[Martha Stewart]].<ref name=\"Yale\">{{cite news|url= http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/09/20/entertainment/main860422.shtml |last=de Vries |first=Lloyd |title=How Martha Coped At 'Yale' |publisher=CBS News |date=20 September 2005 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> By 2004, according to Alexandra Marks of ''[[The Independent]]'', the operating model for Alderson followed \"a punitive rather than a rehabilitative model\".<ref name=\"marks\" />\n\nJohn Benish, the former co-manager of the Alderson Hospitality House, a hospitality establishment where families of Alderson inmates stay, said that FPC Alderson is \"built like a college campus. There is lot of property, a lot of greenery and there is no [[barbed wire]] around.\" The Alderson facility includes two dormitories with 500 inmates each. Inmates live in two person cubicles instead of traditional barred prison cells.<ref>{{cite news|last=Meier |first=Barry |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C05E5D81538F933A0575AC0A9629C8B63 |title=Martha Stewart Assigned to Prison in West Virginia |newspaper=The New York Times |date=30 September 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2004, most prisoners at Alderson were convicted of [[recreational drug]]-related offenses. Esther Heffernan, a sociology professor at [[Edgewood College]], said that throughout history the inmates included \"relatives of famous mobsters and grandmotherly women who embezzled money from banks. You've had a real mixture.\" Hefferman added that in Alderson, which was a \"not undesirable\" place to be confined, the isolation from urban life could be stressful for inmates. She said that the inmates, \"Coming from the streets of [[New York City|New York]] and [[Washington, D.C.|D.C.]],\" were awakened at night by crickets and frogs.<ref>{{cite news|last=Crawford |first=Krysten |url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/09/29/news/newsmakers/martha/index.htm |title=Martha going to 'Camp Cupcake' |publisher=CNN/Money |date=29 September 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> Prisoners are not permitted to patronize Alderson, West Virginia area businesses.<ref>{{cite news|last=Keller |first=Julia |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/703554631.html?dids=703554631:703554631&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |title=It's a gosh-darned good thing: Stewart heads to West Virginia |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=1 October 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011 |quote=They're forbidden to frequent Alderson businesses, so Simms has never trimmed a...}}</ref>\n\nThe facility allows weekend visits, but special hours are available for holidays.<ref name=\"helderman \">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A8664-2004Nov23.html |title=Domestic Diva to Spend Thanksgiving Inside \u2013 Turkey, Few Trimmings For Jailed Media Mogul |first=Rosalind S. |last=Helderman |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=24 November 2004 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> In prior years the families of inmates were allowed past visiting rooms only on [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving Day]] when they could also share in a holiday feast for $1.75.<ref name=\"helderman \" />\n\nFPC Alderson was one of six federal and state prisons participating in the Paws4prisons service dog training program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kyria|title=Some of the DOGs' activities at Federal Prison Camp Alderson (WV) |url= https://paws4people.org/tag/federal-prison-camp/ |website=paws4people foundation|accessdate=23 October 2017 |date=August 22, 2011}}</ref> This program allowed inmates the opportunity to interact and work with dogs.<ref>{{cite web |last=Asbury |first=Kyla |title=Inmate, afraid of dogs, loses lawsuit over broken leg |url= https://wvrecord.com/stories/510606118-inmate-afraid-of-dogs-loses-lawsuit-over-broken-leg |publisher=West Virginia Record |date=22 October 2013 |accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref> This included an academic curriculum where inmates first learn how to train \"shelter-rescue dogs\" and then progress to developing highly trained assistance dogs.<ref>{{cite web |title=The paws4prisons Program |url= https://paws4people.org/our-programs/paws4prisons/ |website=paws4people.org |accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notable inmates (current and former)==\n* Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.\n\n===Violent criminals===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Lolita Lebr\u00f3n]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=22167-069&x=66&y=13 22167-069]\n| Sentence [[commutation of sentence|commuted]] by President [[Jimmy Carter]] in 1979; served 25 years.\n| Member of a group of [[Puerto Rican independence movement|Puerto Rican nationalists]] who opened fire inside the [[US House of Representatives]] in 1954, wounding five Congressmen; served additional prison time in 2001 for trespassing on military property for protesting the [[US Navy]] presence on the Puerto Rican island of [[Vieques]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/03/us/03lebron.html | work=The New York Times | first=Douglas | last=Martin | title=Lolita Lebr\u00f3n, Puerto Rican Nationalist, Dies at 90 | date=3 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_62IjQ-XQScC&pg=PA381&dq=Lolita+Lebr\u00f3n+Alderson+WV |title=Latinas in the United States: a historical encyclopedia |volume=1 |first=Vicki |last=Ru\u00edz |first2=Virginia S\u00e1nchez |last2=Korrol |page=381 |publisher=Indiana University Press |year=2006 |isbn= 978-0-253-34681-0 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[George Weyerhaeuser kidnapping|Margaret Waley]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| Released from custody in 1948 after serving 14 years.\n| Convicted in 1935 of [[kidnapping]] and [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] for her role as an accomplice in the [[George Weyerhaeuser kidnapping|kidnapping of George Weyerhaeuser]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McClary |first=Daryl C. |url=http://www.historylink.org/_content/study_aids/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=7711 |title=the Free Online Encyclopedia of Washington State History |publisher=HistoryLink.org |date=2006-03-27 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Kathryn Kelly]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| Released from custody in 1958 after serving 25 years.\n| Wife of notorious bank robber and murderer George Kelly Barnes, better known as \"[[Machine Gun Kelly]];\" convicted in 1933 of being her husband's accomplice in the [[kidnapping]] of businessman and oil tycoon [[Charles F. Urschel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dillingerswomen.com/articles/kathryn.html |title=Don't Call Us Molls: Kathryn Kelly |publisher=Dillingerswomen.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Lynette Fromme]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=06075-180&x=69&y=26 06075-180]\n| Spent the majority of her sentence at FPC Alderson; released in 2009 after serving 34 years.\n| Follower of [[cult leader]] and [[serial killer]] [[Charles Manson]]; attempted to [[assassinate]] U.S. President [[Gerald Ford]] on September 5, 1975; known by the nickname \"Squeaky.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Busted: Mugshots and Arrest Records of the Famous and Infamous |first=Thomas J. |last=Craughwell |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ll-1WrZvUwsC&pg=PA156&dq=Lynette+Fromme+Alderson+WV |page=156 |publisher=Black Dog & Leventhal|year=2011 |isbn= 978-1-57912-865-4 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-201_162-5241905.html |title=Manson Disciple \"Squeaky\" Fromme Set Free |publisher=CBS News |date=2009-08-14 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Sara Jane Moore]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=04851-180&x=84&y=22 04851-180]\n| imprisoned 1975\u201378, in 1979 she escaped and was recaptured hours later;<ref>{{cite news|url= https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/649221072.html?dids=649221072:649221072&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+06%2C+1979&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Sara+Jane+Moore+Flees%2C+Is+Caught |title=Sara Jane Moore Flees, Is Caught |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=6 February 1979 |accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref> released in 2007, after serving 32 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/12/31/moore.release/index.html|title=Would-be Ford assassin freed from prison on parole - CNN.com|website=www.cnn.com|language=en|access-date=2017-06-09}}</ref>\n| Attempted to assassinate U.S. President [[Gerald Ford]] on September 22, 1975.\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Espionage, Smith Act and \"Supporting the Enemy in Wartime\" prisoners===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Velvalee Dickinson]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}} \n|imprisoned 1944\u20131951<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fbi.gov/about-us/history/famous-cases/velvalee-dickinson-doll-woman |title=Velvalee Dickinson, the \"Doll Woman\" |publisher=FBI |accessdate=17 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502073409/http://www.fbi.gov/about-us/history/famous-cases/velvalee-dickinson-doll-woman |archivedate=2 May 2013 }}</ref>\n| American convicted of espionage against the United States on behalf of Japan.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Iva Toguri D'Aquino]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| Was Held in FPC, Alderson<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F5wukQLkavoC&pg=PA433&dq=Iva+Toguri+D'Aquino+Alderson+WV |title=American women during World War II: an encyclopedia |first= Doris |last=Weatherford |page=433 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2009 |isbn= 978-0-415-99475-0 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n| American citizen who participated in English-language [[propaganda]] broadcast transmitted by Radio Tokyo to Allied soldiers in the South Pacific during [[World War II]]; known as \"Tokyo Rose.\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Mildred Gillars]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n|imprisoned 1950\u201356<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mcbRtSJ2EDkC&pg=PA223&dq=Mildred+Gillars+Alderson+WV |title=Axis Sally: The American Voice of Nazi Germany |first=Richard |last=Lucas |publisher=Casemate Publishers |year=2010 |isbn= 978-1-935149-43-9 |pages=223, 292 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/01/obituaries/mildred-gillars-87-axis-sally-during-war.html|title=Obituaries: Mildred Gillars, 87, Axis Sally During War |newspaper=The New York Times |date=1 July 1988 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n| American who supplied propaganda broadcasts for [[Nazi Germany]]; known as \"Axis Sally.\"\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Elizabeth Gurley Flynn]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| imprisoned 1955\u201357<ref>{{cite book|title=The Alderson story: my life as a political prisoner |first=Elizabeth Gurley |last=Flynn |publisher=International Publishers |year=1963}}</ref>\n| American leftist leader and co-founder of [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU), a [[Smith Act]] prisoner\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Claudia Jones]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| imprisoned 1955\u201357<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackhistorymonthuk.co.uk/features/claudia_jones.html|title=Claudia Jones|publisher=Black History Month|accessdate=29 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019212347/http://www.blackhistorymonthuk.co.uk/features/claudia_jones.html|archive-date=19 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| Trinidadian-born child-immigrant journalist and National Executive member of the [[Communist Party of the United States]], a Smith Act prisoner. After release, deported to the [[United Kingdom]], founded the [[Notting Hill Carnival]]\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Corrupt public officials===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Monica Conyers]] \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=43693-039&x=94&y=13 43693-039]\n| Released from custody on May 16, 2013 after serving 3 years.\n| [[Detroit City Council]] member from 2005 to 2009 and wife of former-Congressman [[John Conyers]]; pleaded guilty to [[bribery]] in 2009 for accepting $60,000 from a waste management company in return for her helping the company win a $1.2 billion contract with the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/story?id=7938249&page=1#.UB4nWVJdDyI |title=Monica Conyers, Wife of Judiciary Chairman Rep. John Conyers Pleads Guilty to Bribery - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2009-06-26 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/10/monica-conyers-wife-to-jo_n_494305.html|title=Monica Conyers, Wife To John Conyers, Sentenced To 3 Years In Prison For Detroit Bribes|date=May 10, 2010|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-08-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Meg Scott Phipps]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=23786-056&x=82&y=6 23786-056]\n| Released from custody in 2007 after serving 3 years.\n| [[North Carolina Department of Agriculture & Consumer Services|North Carolina Agriculture Commissioner]] from 2001 to 2003; pleaded guilty in 2003 to [[extortion]], [[mail fraud]], and [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] for accepting thousands of dollars in illegal cash payments, falsifying campaign finance reports, and extorting money from carnival operators with the promise of state contracts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/news/local/story/109254/ |title=Phipps To Spend Four Years In Prison For State Ag Department Scandal |publisher=WRAL.com |date=2004-03-02 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digtriad.com/news/article/83437/0/Meg-Scott-Phipps-Released-From-Prison |title=Meg Scott Phipps Released From Prison |publisher=digtriad.com |date=2007-04-23 |accessdate=2015-10-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130121105945/http://www.digtriad.com/news/article/83437/0/Meg-Scott-Phipps-Released-From-Prison |archivedate=2013-01-21 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Financial criminals===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Stacey Pomrenke]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 19241-084<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.bop.gov/inmateloc/ | title=Inmate Locator | author= | publisher=bop.gov | date= | accessdate=21 January 2017}}</ref>\n|Released in 2018 after serving a 23-month sentence.\n|Former Bristol Virginia Utilities (BVU) Chief Financial Officer (CFO) convicted on one count of conspiracy to commit tax fraud, three counts of making false statements to the IRS, one count of program fraud, two counts of extortion, one count of conspiracy to commit wire fraud and six counts of wire fraud.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Martha Stewart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=55170-054&x=69&y=25 55170-054]\n| Released from custody in 2005 after serving 5 months. \n| American business magnate, television host, author, and magazine publisher; convicted in 2004 of [[obstruction of justice]] and lying to federal prosecutors investigating [[insider trading]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/03/05/news/companies/martha_verdict/ | work=CNN | title=Stewart convicted on all charges | date=5 March 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A54591-2004Jul16.html | work=The Washington Post | title=Martha Stewart Sentenced to 5 Months in Prison | date=16 July 2004}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Esther Reed]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=IDSearch&needingMoreList=false&IDType=IRN&IDNumber=40024-424&x=80&y=21 40024-424]\n| Released from custody in 2011 after serving 3 years.\n| Former [[US Secret Service]] Most-Wanted Fugitive; pleaded guilty to [[fraud]] and [[identity theft]] for falsely assuming several identities, including that of missing person Brooke Henson, in order to steal money and gain entrance to [[Ivy League]] universities; Reed was featured on the television program ''[[America's Most Wanted]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.secretservice.gov/FY2008_AnnualReport_WM.pdf|title=United States Secret Service Fiscal Year 2008 Annual Report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825185354/http://www.secretservice.gov/FY2008_AnnualReport_WM.pdf|archive-date=August 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1473463/|title=America's Most Wanted: America Fights Back : Esther Reed Capture|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Diane Hathaway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=Diane&Middle=&LastName=Hathaway&Race=W&Sex=F&Age=&x=90&y=11 48069-039]\n| Released from custody in 2014 after serving 366 days.\n| [[Michigan Supreme Court|Former Michigan Supreme Court Justice]] convicted of mortgage fraud.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ross Jones |url=http://www.wxyz.com/dpp/news/local_news/investigations/with-hathaway-now-a-felon-gov-snyder-mulls-her-replacement |title=With Hathaway now a felon, Gov. Snyder mulls her replacement |publisher=WXYZ.com |date=2013-01-30 |accessdate=2015-10-09}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Others===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=13%|Inmate name\n!width=10%|Register number\n!width=28%|Status\n!width=49%|Details\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Billie Holiday]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unlisted{{efn|name=\"Unlisted\"|Inmates released from custody prior to 1982 are not listed on the Federal Bureau of Prisons website.}}\n| imprisoned 1947-48<ref>{{cite book |title=Billie Holiday |first=Magdalena |last=Alagna |pages=60\u201370 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lh3rwxxv2z0C&pg=PT72&dq=Billie+Holiday+Alderson+WV |publisher=Rosen Publishing |year=2003 |isbn= 978-0-8239-3640-3 |accessdate=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n| American jazz singer and songwriter arrested for possession of narcotics on May 19, 1947 and sentenced to serve a year and a day, but released for good behavior on March 16, 1948.\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of U.S. federal prisons]]\n*[[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]\n*[[Incarceration in the United States]]\n{{Portal|United States|Politics}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons-inline|Federal Prison Camp, Alderson